INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(366,'paragraph',NULL,'amplitude<span class="ITS_index">Amplitude</span>. The amplitude is a scaling factor that determines how large the cosine signal will be. Since the function <span class="ITS_EQ">eq:general-cosine oscillates between <span class="ITS_EQ">+A</span> and <span class="ITS_EQ">-A</span>.',2,5,2);
INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(367,'equation',NULL,'\phi',2,5,3);
INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(368,'equation',NULL,'x(t)=A\sin (\omega_0 t + \phi^{\prime})',2,5,3);
INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(369,'equation',NULL,'\phi =\phi^{\prime} -\pi/2',2,5,3);
INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(370,'index',NULL,'Phase shift',2,5,3);
INSERT INTO dSPFirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(371,'paragraph',NULL,'phase shift<span class="ITS_index">Phase shift</span>. The units of phase shift must be radians, since the argument of the cosine must be in radians. We will generally prefer to use the cosine function when defining the phase shift. If we happen to have a formula containing sine, e.g., <span class="ITS_EQ">x(t)=A\prime)</span>, then we can rewrite it in terms of cosine if we use the equivalence property in Table~<span class="ITS_keyword">tab:trig-props</span>. The result is: \prime)=A\prime-<span class="ITS_EQ">\phi =\phi^{\prime -eq:general-cosine. For simplicity and to prevent confusion, we often avoid using the sine function.',2,5,3);
